        "type": "message",
        "text": "<@U012XRK1371>\n&gt; So, the idea is to structure the web application as set of pre-defined concepts?\n&gt; Then these concepts are composed together declaratively as a html tree data structure (coded by someone or generated by composer UI).\n&gt; And under the hood, there is something that coordinates the client-server communication (by handling eval\/exec), with possible transaction like synchronization for certain events?\nYes, that is correct.\n\n&gt; I think of concept as a “process” (that runs on frontend\/backend) with eval and exec operations. \nYes, that’s good. Note that a concept can have multiple eval\/exec operations (one set of eval\/exec per concept component)\n\n&gt; So if I have two concepts, how can I combine them?\nFor example, let’s say you have a book review app and you’d like to allow your users to input book reviews with a comment and a star rating. So, you create a review component and include the `create-comment` component of the `comment` concept and the `rate-target` component of the `rating` concept:\n```...\n&lt;comment.create-comment \/&gt;\n&lt;rating.rate-target \/&gt;\n...```\nAt this point, your users can create a review comment and a rating separately, but we want to compose them and have the exec run together, so we do two things: (1) we wrap them with a `dv.tx`; and (2) we wire a generated  unique ID to both concept components so that the entities they eventually save (the rating and comment) are linked by the shared ID:\n```...\n&lt;dv.tx&gt;\n  &lt;dv.gen-id \/&gt;\n  &lt;comment.create-comment id=dv.gen-id.id targetId=$postId \/&gt;\n  &lt;rating.rate-target targetId=dv.gen-id.id \/&gt;\n  &lt;dv.button \/&gt;\n&lt;\/dv.tx&gt;\n...```\n When the user clicks on the `dv.button`, both the `exec` of `create-comment`  and the `exec` of `rate-target` run together at the same time.",
        "user": "UP7N4QVK2",
        "ts": "1592293121.327000",
